2026-05-04 | Sum of Waviness in a Range

	Question
Return total waviness in the given range.
	Key Insight
Checking every number individually is impossible for large ranges.
Whenever a digit becomes the third digit of a sequence:
		a b c
we can determine whether
		b is a peak or valley.
So while building a number digit-by-digit,
we only need to remember:
		1. previous digit
		2. second previous digit
This is a classic Digit DP.
	Approach
1.	Create function:
		F(x)
		= total waviness of all numbers
		  from 0 to x.
2.	Use Digit DP state:
		position
		tight
		started
		last digit
		second last digit
3.	When adding a new digit d:
		check whether
		previous digit forms:
				peak
				or
				valley
		with neighbors:
				secondLast
				and d
4.	Add contribution to DP.
5.	Answer:
		F(num2) - F(num1 - 1)
	Time Complexity
	O(positions × 10 × states)
	Approximately O(20 × 10 × states)
	Space Complexity
	O(states)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    struct Node {
        long long cnt;
        long long waviness;
    };
    string s;
    Node dp[20][11][11][2][2];
    bool vis[20][11][11][2][2];
    Node solve(int pos,
               int prev1,
               int prev2,
               bool started,
               bool tight) {
        if(pos == s.size())
            return {1, 0};
        if(prev1 != 10 &&
           prev2 != 10 &&
           vis[pos][prev1][prev2][started][tight])
            return dp[pos][prev1][prev2][started][tight];
        int limit = tight ? s[pos] - '0' : 9;
        Node res = {0, 0};
        for(int d = 0; d <= limit; d++) {
            bool ntight =
                tight && (d == limit);
            if(!started && d == 0) {
                Node nxt =
                    solve(pos + 1,
                          10,
                          10,
                          false,
                          ntight);
                res.cnt += nxt.cnt;
                res.waviness += nxt.waviness;
            }
            else {
                int add = 0;
                if(prev1 != 10 &&
                   prev2 != 10) {
                    if((prev1 > prev2 && prev1 > d) ||
                       (prev1 < prev2 && prev1 < d))
                        add = 1;
                }
                int nprev2 =
                    (prev1 == 10 ? d : prev1);
                Node nxt =
                    solve(pos + 1,
                          d,
                          nprev2,
                          true,
                          ntight);
                res.cnt += nxt.cnt;
                res.waviness +=
                    nxt.waviness +
                    (long long)add * nxt.cnt;
            }
        }
        if(prev1 != 10 &&
           prev2 != 10) {
            vis[pos][prev1][prev2][started][tight]
                = true;
            dp[pos][prev1][prev2][started][tight]
                = res;
        }
        return res;
    }
    long long calc(long long x) {
        if(x < 0)
            return 0;
        memset(vis, 0, sizeof(vis));
        s = to_string(x);
        return solve(0,10,10,false,true).waviness;
    }
    long long totalWaviness(long long num1,
                            long long num2) {
        return calc(num2) -
               calc(num1 - 1);
    }
};
	Key Insight
A digit's peak/valley status can only be determined when both its neighbors are known. Therefore, while constructing numbers digit-by-digit, keeping track of the last two digits is sufficient. This makes the problem a classic Digit DP where we count total waviness over an entire range without enumerating every number.
